If you ever ask how do I use ItemID with modded items or how do I get the projectileID of a modded projectile, read this. First off, IDs of things from Terraria are accessed by the `SomethingID.ThingName` pattern. For example: `ItemID.Acorn`, `ProjectileID.WoodenArrowFriendly`, `NPCID.BlueSlime`. Things from mods are accessed by calling `ModContent.SomethingType<ThingName>()`. For example: `ModContent.ItemType<ExampleBlock>())`, `ModContent.ProjectileType<ExampleBullet>()`, `ModContent.NPCType<FlutterSlime>()`. We use the words "id" and "type" interchangeably, in the end, they are just unique numbers that match up with the item in question. If you are curious, here is another example, this time showing how to replace a vanilla item with a modded item if you are copying from a code example: ```recipe.AddIngredient(ItemID.LastPrism);
recipe.AddIngredient(ModContent.ItemType<BossItem>());
recipe.AddIngredient(3541); 
// 3541 and ItemID.LastPrism are equal. You can look up ID values on the wiki: https://github.com/tModLoader/tModLoader/wiki/Vanilla-Content-IDs#item-ids```
Here are some examples of common ERRORs modders make:
```recipe.AddIngredient(ItemID.MyModItem); // ItemID is only for vanilla items.
recipe.AddIngredient(ItemID.3541); // This is just wrong, don't do this.
recipe.AddIngredient(ItemID.mod.ItemType("BossItem")); // Don't do this either.
recipe.AddIngredient(ModContent.ItemType(BossItem)); // Remember not to forget the angle brackets in ItemType method calls
recipe.AddIngredient(ItemID.Sand Block); // ItemIDs never have spaces. When in doubt, look them up
recipe.AddIngredient(ModContent.ItemType<ItemID.LastPrism>()); // Don't try to mix ItemIDs and mod.ItemType.```

If you ever ask how do I use ItemID with modded items or how do I get the projectileID of a modded projectile, read this. First off, IDs of things from Terraria are accessed by the `SomethingID.ThingName` pattern. For example: `ItemID.Acorn`, `ProjectileID.WoodenArrowFriendly`, `NPCID.BlueSlime`. Things from mods are accessed by calling `mod.SomethingType("ThingName")`. For example: `mod.ItemType("ExampleBlock")`, `mod.ProjectileType("ExampleBullet")`, `mod.NPCType("FlutterSlime")`. We use the words "id" and "type" interchangeably, in the end, they are just unique numbers that match up with the item in question. If you are curious, here is another example, this time showing how to replace a vanilla item with a modded item if you are copying from a code example: ```Item.NewItem(npc.getRect(), ItemID.LastPrism);
Item.NewItem(npc.getRect(), mod.ItemType("BossItem"));
Item.NewItem(npc.getRect(), 3541); 
// 3541 and ItemID.LastPrism are equal. You can look up ID values on the wiki: https://github.com/tModLoader/tModLoader/wiki/Vanilla-Content-IDs#item-ids```
Here are some examples of common ERRORs modders make:
```Item.NewItem(npc.getRect(), ItemID.3541); // This is just wrong, don't do this.
Item.NewItem(npc.getRect(), ItemID.mod.ItemType("BossItem")); // Don't do this either.
Item.NewItem(npc.getRect(), mod.ItemType(BossItem)); // Remember not to forget the quotes in ItemType method calls
Item.NewItem(npc.getRect(), ItemID.Sand Block); // ItemIDs never have spaces. When in doubt, look them up
Item.NewItem(npc.getRect(), mod.ItemType("ItemID.LastPrism")); // Don't try to mix ItemIDs and mod.ItemType.```

