You can color tooltips using [color chat tags](<https://terraria.wiki.gg/wiki/Chat#Color>). You can localize this easily with format arguments.
First, setup your localization key properly:
```SomeKey: "[c/{0}:Some text]"```The `""` are important here, otherwise our localisation file won't load properly. You can omit them in a multiline tooltip, however
Next, we need to apply our color in code. This is usually done in `ModifyTooltips`:
```cs
float pulseAmount = Main.mouseTextColor / 255f;
Color textColor = someColor * pulseAmount;
string coloredText = Language.GetText("SomeKey").Format(textColor.Hex3());
// Go on to use coloredText```
The `pulseAmount` is the natural pulsing that tooltips have, you can omit this if your use case doesn't require it. Also, the `.Hex3()` call is important, this will format our color so it works with the chat tag correctly

Shown below is an example of standard manual projectile drawing.  This code assumes that you're using this within a `ModProjectile` class.
```cs
// Restarts the spritebatch if a shader was used
Main.instance.PrepareDrawnProjectileDrawing(Projectile);
// Sets up drawing parameters
var texture = TextureAssets.Projectile[Type].Value;
var source = texture.Frame(1, Main.projFrames[Type], 0, Projectile.frame);
var flip = Projectile.spriteDirection == -1 ? SpriteEffects.FlipHorizontally : SpriteEffects.None;
// Actually draws it
Main.EntitySpriteDraw(texture, Projectile.Center, source, lightColor, Projectile.rotation, source.Size() / 2f, Projectile.scale, flip);
```

You can easily swap existing vanilla textures for your own using a few different methods. The easiest but most limiting way is by setting it in `TextureAssets`. In a `Load` hook, set `TextureAssets.SomeCollection[type]` to your own texture, and re-set it in `Unload`. Ex:
```cs
Load:
  // If you'd prefer to cache the existing texture and replace it later on, do that before assigning to it
  // waterBoltTexture = TextureAssets.Projectile[ProjectileID.WaterBolt];
  TextureAssets.Projectile[ProjectileID.WaterBolt] = ModContent.Request<Texture2D>("MyEpicMod/SomePath/SomeTexture");

Unload:
  // TextureAssets.Projectile[ProjectileID.WaterBolt] = waterBoltTexture; // If you cached it
  TextureAssets.Projectile[ProjectileID.WaterBolt] = ModContent.Request<Texture2D>($"Terraria/Images/Projectile_{ProjectileID.WaterBolt}");
```
Note: This method is limited, it won't allow you to change the animation or any other drawn effects, consider using `PreDraw` if you need this
